  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Coronary artery disease (CAD) is the leading cause of morbidity and mortality in developed
      countries. In addition, many patients suffer from valvular and aortic disease. Although
      various tools are available to identify patients with cardiovascular (CV) disease at risk for
      major adverse cardiac events (MACE), the identification of these patients remains a clinical
      challenge.

      One promising avenue is the use of different serum biomarkers involved in atherothrombosis
      which could provide an easy and cost-effective step in risk stratification.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
